	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64587605"><p>You're fighting the wrong enemy bro.</p><p>You might want to look at which countries are currently and have had historically the lowest CO2 per kWh figures.</p><p>Renewables are very much most likely the cheaper cost but there are still a few knotty problems with aren't currently solved. Renewables have no inertia. That's a solvable problem with rotary compensators. Easy enough, but it'll need to be done at scale. The other problem is that renewable performance is on a large regional/small continental scale.</p><p>This needs se<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

