		<div id="comment_body_64587967"><p><div class="quote"><p>In all your pro-nuclear ranting and posturing, why do you always ignore cost? At the end of the day, all other forms of clean energy are far cheaper.</p></div><p>That was absolutely not the case until just fairly recently, and even now it's pretty questionable once you actually include grid firming costs. You need a looooot of extra capacity and storage.</p><p>They examine a couple of clean power scenarios here:<br><span class="substr"> </span> <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2P3A_-pcEEA" title="youtube.com">https://www.youtube.com/watch?...</a> [youtube.com] </p><p>tl;dr in these snaps:<br> <a href="https://i.imgur.com/BBuSCIO.png" title="imgur.com">https://i.imgur.com/BBuSCIO.pn...</a> [imgur.com] <br> <a href="https://i.imgur.com/EFg3o1q.png" title="imgur.com">https://i.imgur.com/EFg3o1q.pn...</a> [imgur.com] <br> <a href="https://i.imgur.com/easLlnW.png" title="imgur.com">https://i.imgur.com/easLlnW.pn...</a> [imgur.com] </p><p>Decisions to kill off nuclear and subsidize solar/wind had been made decades ago.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64587967">

