			<h4><a id="comment_link_64587769" name="comment_link_64587769" href="//politics.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23371635&amp;cid=64587769" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64587769)" >Re: I want the more costly option</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64587769" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64587769); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~kenh">kenh</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~kenh">( 9056 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64587769"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64587769"><p>In the U.S. we subsidize solar to an amazing extent, we subsidize:</p><p>- Basic Research<br>- Factory Construction<br>- Panel Purchase<br>- Installer Training<br>- Installation</p><p>And we require power companies to buy any surplus electricity the panels generate at a higher rate that the power company can buy electricity from another company, even if the power company has no need/use for it.</p><p> <b>If Solar is so cheap, can we stop the above subsidies and policies? Or, is solar power cheaper BECAUSE of the subsidies?</b> </p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64587769">

