<div id="comment_status_64587229" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64587229" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64587229" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64587229" name="comment_link_64587229" href="//politics.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23371635&amp;cid=64587229" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64587229)" >Easy, rational explanation</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64587229" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64587229); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~tiqui">tiqui</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~tiqui">( 1024021 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64587229">		
		on Saturday June 29, 2024 @04:15AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//politics.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23371635&amp;cid=64587229">#64587229</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64587229"><p>First: <b>Energy Density</b>. Middle-aged and older right-leaning people tend to be aware of many years of hype about this or that "clean" <i>miracle</i> energy source, and the fact that they NEVER pan-out as actual replacements for fossil fuels - for the simple reason that fossil fuels pack a LOT of energy into a small space. Solar and wind are rather diffuse, and they're not constant or reliable, so they require storage systems (batteries) which bring along their own set of problems. There's simply nothing optimal about "renewables" other than that they optimally align with a certain political ideology which seems to care little about costs for average people.</p><p>Second: <b>Propaganda</b>.  Middle-aged and older right-leaning people tend to be wary of anything relentlessly pushed by the political left, and forced by government, in a land where people are supposed to have freedom. If something is truly a superior solution in a free-market system, then it will stand, and win, on its own, without government subsidies (or bans on the alternatives). If government has to FORCE people to move to the new shiny object, then the new shiny object is clearly not as good as what it is replacing. These skeptical folks have seen the promises and they have seen the results, and they do not like the results. Instead of things getting cheaper and more plentiful with the newest stuff, things are getting more expensive and harder to get. It's been said before that a conservative is a liberal who's been mugged.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64587229">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64587229" class="btn link" href="//politics.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23371635&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64587229" onclick="D2.replyTo(64587229); return false;">Reply to This</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
